segments.text: was again coordinating their activities with the registrar and admissions liaison with the president, provost, activities there, dealing with the curriculum matters, those kinds of things.
Ed was excellent to work with in the sense that obviously there were times when people thought they should be admitted
He was always perfectly willing to counsel with those people.
If my staff wasn't able to handle it and I was not able to handle it, then Ed would take over the chore and would handle the situation.
I think Ed was always fair with the students on the thing.
He was fairly fair with us.
Obviously, sometimes he felt the student should be admitted when somebody else may not have, and that was all right, too.
I mean, it was his job to make that decision, I think.
Sometimes did he overrule a decision you all made on admissions?
Yeah, in a sense that we had a kind of an appeals process fixed up.
Not only a written appeal thing, which Ed was involved in,
a lot of times, but verbal appeals.

A lot of times, a person might come to Gale, for instance, and want to be admitted, and it didn't meet requirements, and they weren't satisfied with talking to Gale, so they'd want to talk with me, and they'd talk with me, and they weren't satisfied talking to me, and they'd want to talk with Ed.
And there were some occasions when Ed felt that they should be admitted after maybe I had recommended they not be.
I just told him that I
couldn't admit them, but they're perfectly welcome to talk to the dean if they want to.
And he sometimes would see it the way I did, and sometimes would see it differently the way I did, which didn't make any difference to me.
What was the most common argument for this person to be admitted who didn't meet the stated remission requirements?
What was their most likely argument?
reason?
It's hard to say.
Probably the fact that, you know, I know he hasn't done it, but I know he's got the ability to do it, and it's just a matter of him getting down to do it.
These kinds of things.
I'll give you a couple of examples, like at least one, two, of things, you know, they never got to Ed, but there are appeals, I think.
One,
was a young man who had multiple dystrophy, I believe.
He was confined to a wheelchair, and I do not, he was a muscle problem and that.
And he came, I guess they set up an interview probably.
Anyway, talked with he and his parents, come to find out
his parents were both graduates of the University of Texas in Austin, but for some reason he decided he wouldn't come to Texas A&M.
And that was the time, if you remember Haskell, we really didn't have great facilities for students who were in wheelchairs.
We were working on it and doing a reasonable job, I think.
But they had talked, I believe, with the people in the
handicapped student's office.
I don't know what it was called at that time.
But they were satisfied that he could handle a situation and that they would provide him with whatever help that he might need on the thing.
And anyway, they wanted him admitted.
And it wasn't that, I don't remember exactly, I feel relatively sure he had met the admission requirement.
There was certainly some concern
about his being able to handle them.
For example, they could just get him admitted for a year.
They didn't think he'd live a year.
Well, he got admitted and not only did he live a year, he lived long enough to graduate
And in talking with one of our former regents who knows him quite well, he is now a lawyer and doing very well.
The young man, you know, he's married, has, I think, a family.
But anyway, it's a real success story in the fact that that.
I have another girl, and I do not know really whatever happened to her.
I don't know that she did graduate.
She had rheumatoid arthritis so bad that she could barely
get along.
Her hands were crippled and she was kind of pumped.
And again, her parents were asking and I'm not too sure, I don't think that they had a problem, but something had happened that she didn't meet admission requirements.
But anyway, we admitted her and sure enough, four years later I saw her graduate by walking across the stage.
And it's those kind of things which made the experience that I
I remember the success stories, a few of them, a whole lot more than I remember those that we turned down.
And a lot of them that we admitted, periodically some kid would come by and says, just wanted to let you know you admitted me, you made an exception, and I graduated.
And I even received, at one time, a copy of a diploma in a tube the guy had sent me.
And he says, I just wanted you to know that I made it.
And I still have a copy of the diploma in there.
Now, were these appeals for admission, were they any more likely to come from small towns than big cities or working class, white collar?
Was there any generalization about the kind of families they came from and geographically?
As I recall, they did.
I mean, it's kind of across the board.
The thing which I enjoyed...
in the early years was the fact that we were given the opportunity if we thought an exception should be made to make it.
For the most part, I told my staff that if you think an exception ought to be made, go ahead and make it.
You don't have to come to me and ask about it.
If you want to, fine, we'll discuss it.
But you can do that.
I felt I had the same thing with Dean Cooper.
He never said, don't make any exceptions.
He says, you admit those you think should be admitted.
But at the same time, he says, if you want my input on the thing, I'll be glad to do that on the thing.
Did you ever get any
communication, letter, phone call, or anything else from anyone, quote, in the higher administration to admit so-and-so?
In the administration, yeah.
Again, if the president felt someone should be admitted or the vice president
president or provost, whom everyone felt somebody should be admitted, that was their prerogative.

But I'm thinking about at this point, Williams and Byers or Williams and Calhoun, was it their style to communicate with you or Ed and say, I got a letter and I told them that so-and-so would be admitted?
Or would they pass it down to you or Ed?
They would generally pass it down to Ed.
I got very few calls directly.
And we, I guess in all honesty, we got very few demands for admitting students.
And I soon learned, at least in my mind as a rationalization, that it wasn't worth making some
person who could do the university some good to make them mad just because we didn't feel a student could be admitted.

I never hesitated to tell anybody that I thought it was a mistake as far as the student is concerned because in the fact we're doing the student a disservice I think rather than doing some particular person a disservice on the time.
We had one chancellor
who I really enjoyed working with in the sense that he never called and said he'd met somebody.
He often called and said, would you look at a person's application and tell me what you think about it.
Who is that?
All right.
Because to me that's complimentary.
It is.
It's Dr. Atkinson.
Perry Atkinson.
Perry Atkinson.
And I don't recall that he was always, would you look and see what you've got and let me know.
And usually I wouldn't.
I would always look, and I would say, here's why I think we shouldn't, or there may be a chance if you feel like we should.
And most oftentimes, he said, I think you're right.
It would not be a good service to the student.
Because that seems to me to be a very sensitive and thoughtful way to handle it.
Let's go back to Williams and Calhoun replaced Byers.
and not long after Dr. Williams got here, describe working with them.
I was pretty well insulated, I think.
Ed worked with them mostly.
Occasionally, Dr. Williams would call and ask about a student, as I recall, but very seldom.
Generally, what contact we had with it was through Ed's office on there.
And when did you all move over to the new building?
The new building, that was Heaton Hall?
Yeah.
Early 80s, I guess.
I was in charge of remodeling the thing.
The old bookstore.
The old bookstore, yeah.
People asked, where are you?
And I said, we're in Heaton Hall.
They said, well, where is that?
And I said, well, do you remember the old bookstore?
And they said, no.
And I said, do you remember the old laundry?
And so it had three or four different functions over the years.
Oh, I'd forgotten.
It was the laundry before it was the bookstore, wasn't it?
I think it was the laundry before the bookstore.
so people you would recognize it from that and at least 70s and you had good space then yeah and we had good space we had more than uh we had where we were that's for sure uh it
It wasn't the best of locations in the sense that it had no parking around it.
But as far as we as operating in there were concerned, we had adequate space.
And as we got different kinds of equipment, it even got a little better.
We had originally planned to move the old photostat machine over there, which is a monster.
which was taking up a lot of room.
Back at the time, just before we got ready to move it over, they decided, no, we're not going to move that.
We're going to go with a different kind of a transcript maker.
So we didn't have to do that, which gave us a little more space there in the registrar's side of the thing.
Did you have to worry with transcripts, or was admissions only?
Admissions only.
I didn't have to worry about the transcripts with all of the records keeping.
Summarize the...
ritual routine problems of transfer admissions?
Transfer admissions is a real problem in the sense that students would take coursework at other schools which may or may not fit in with our curriculum here.
It got better as statewide we began to get more cooperation

I think as I recall and you may remember too through some legislation which was done probably which required schools to do certain things but the admissions and registrars throughout the state had gotten together too and were doing a lot of cooperative work so that we had some core courses which
we could all identify with in the first two years.
And you get into your upper division courses, then it got a little more complicated as far as what course would be equivalent to another course.
But the transfer students comprised about
I guess, of our new students each year.
I may be wrong on that, but most of them came in in September.
We had a good number come in in January.
We had very few freshmen come in in January term.
And we worked with the junior colleges throughout the state trying to give them

our course numbers and their equivalents so that a student, if he went to another junior college or community college, they would know from the very beginning what courses they ought to take in order to have that account for a specific course at Texas A&M.
It worked real well as long as the student didn't start changing curriculum.
When the student would start out in beds and didn't want to change over to engineering, obviously, quote, he lost some courses.
He didn't really lose the course credit, but he had courses which he couldn't use on that program.
Had he been at A&M and done the same thing, he would have still been in the same situation, though.
But that's where the, that's usually, it's always the biggest gripe.
I lost hours when I transferred to Texas A&M, and they really didn't lose them.
They had taken coursework, which wouldn't count on a degree program.
Were there any big transfer sources for us?
Did we get more transfers from these schools?
Well, the biggest one probably was still Blinn, because a lot of students went to Blinn and they were transferring.
When they opened the campus here in Bryan, it really got to be a feeder source.
got a lot from Houston Community College, you'd get a lot from Tarrant County Community College system and from Dallas where they had, and San Antonio, where they had the big community colleges.
Some of the smaller community colleges you might have given two or three a year, but others you'd give fifty, a hundred, or whatever the situation may be.
And were any of the programs here getting more transfers than the others?
Probably, and probably because they were larger.
I mean, I'm sure engineering, I'm guessing now, would probably get more transfers than would, say, liberal arts, maybe, or some of the smaller colleges at that time.
As the liberal arts college got bigger, they were probably getting more transfer students, too.
But early on, it was mostly agriculture and engineering.
Which institutions were the most pleasant to work with on transfers?
I really don't know what I could say.
I didn't work directly and transfer it with them that way, but we had, I think, a good working relationship with most all of them.
We knew each other through the professional organizations.
And, you know, if we had a problem, I can remember a fellow at Tyler Junior College
But again, if he had a problem, if a kid came in and said, I've got a problem, can't get something transferred, he wouldn't fuss.
He'd call us up and say, what's going on down there?
And we could usually work out the problem on the thing.
A lot of times, parents would fuss, would complain back to the community college.
It was a matter of, and I say miscommunication, either we didn't communicate properly or the student hadn't done what they were supposed to do to begin with.
But we tried, and I really thank you, we had a good working relationship with all the community colleges.

We tried to, early on, they had college days just like the high schools did, and we would try to have a representative teach one of the junior college college days so we could talk to the students as well as talk to the

representative from the college to let them know what courses they needed to take and how to google that transfer and so forth and i'm assuming that many of the problems i'm putting the word problem in quotation marks from the student and or the parents point of view came from the student's failure to communicate clearly to the parents what the problem was with the transfer
With the loss of hours, as you were mentioning a while ago,
with the failure for the student to take at the junior college the kinds of courses that would be countable toward a degree here.
I mean, that's probably correct.
Again, we felt like we were doing a very good job in letting the student know what they should take.
Obviously, some things fell through the cracks, but if the student planned, we thought, there was no reason why they couldn't
Just interface from the community college right over into the university without any loss at all.
And I think for the most part, most of them probably did.
All right, now we're going from 71 in your service to what year?
19, January 93 is when I retired.
Okay, so 22 years.
In those 22 years, did we become more selective gradually in admissions?
Yes.
Do you remember any particular times when those changes were made?
I think we went to, I recall that we started off at top half and 800 on the SAT, and I don't remember the, I think at 18 on the ACT, but I may be wrong on that, but let's talk about SAT.
We went from that, and I believe it was in the early,
80s that we jumped to a criteria which said uh 1200 in the bottom quarter 1100 in the second quarter and a thousand in the top quarter with an automatic admission now if you had

less than the thousand the top quarter and I think down to 800 we would we did in what we call a review process where we would look individually at the application to see what courses they took what high school they came from what their scores were what letters of recommendation they may have and so forth so we had an automatic admission we had a those admitted by review
Then we had those who were denied, and then those who were denied fit again fit into the two categories of summer school and not summer school.
However, at that time, summer school became more restrictive in that
we limited the number that we could take because we had to, as we began to put in some kinds of enrollment control, which started somewhere around 86, 87, I've forgotten what it was.
We had to make some kind of prediction of how many we were going to get out of the summer school.
So we would know, we tried to get a freshman class of X number at that time.
So we were restricting it more and more toward a limited enrollment of freshmen.
How were those admission decisions, admission requirement decisions?
Do you remember how they were made, how they were shaped?
And where I'm headed is, were those changes made in a fashion that you think, in hindsight, worked well?
Statistically, I think they were.
I think they were, the cutoff scores and stuff were, they were run through models which the
the Academic Counseling Center, is that the correct term?
The Management and Testing, excuse me, that's what it is.
They ran some models, and they said if the students meet these requirements, they ought to be able to go ahead and graduate.
And then it says there are others who, if they meet certain requirements, still should be able to.
But again, we wanted to, for ease of operation, I mean, probably,
If I had had my druthers, we would have operated like the University of North Carolina did in that they review every application individually.
Well, we just didn't have the staff to review every application individually and they were not inclined, and I don't know that we asked for,
to give us a staff to do that.
It just takes a lot of people.
They had, I think when I visited, when they had 24 reviewers working year-round, I had a director of freshman admissions and three clerks or something like this.
So we decided that we would take a group that we felt comfortable with and admit those automatically.
Another group which we felt could

probably be successful but we couldn't take them all but try to review those and take the best ones out of there and again apply not just the criteria class rank and a test score which is those two are together are the best predictors they're not perfect but they're the best but there are some others who there are other factors which we could consider oh now we're now we're into important territory
so stay with this let's make believe that that I'm the Senate now and what if you only had one factor what would be the most important factor to look at is it class rank or is it test score I
I would look at class rank if I only had one factor to look at.
I would look at where he ranks in that class.
Okay, now let's go to the other extreme.
What is the best of all possible combinations based on your experience?
Well, again, I think the combination of test score and class rank is the biggest two predictors.
All right, but what else?
Would you look at anything else?
Yeah, I would want to look at the high school they came from.
whether, again, class rank in a small school is important, class rank in a big school is important.
You can look at other activities which they participate in, whether you're talking about athletics or whether you're talking about
for the class officers or their extracurricular activities and things like that, which they did.
Some students, well, they had to work to help support the family.
Some students, I'm sure, were on their own even, those kind of things.
And it's hard, you know, you get down, when you get past, I think, class rank and test score, there are a lot of little things which can add to it.
Which one is the most important?
I would hate to say, but there are a lot of factors which you can look at and make a better overall picture on the thing, though.
In terms of the likelihood of their success at A&M, of the activities in high school, which were the most valuable activities?
Is being a class officer more important than athletics?
is being involved in a number of organizations?

I don't know I need to say I think I really think the leadership properties are probably very important to them and I can think of an example when we were this is early on we were really trying to get National Merit students here and I remember
I don't know what the situation was.
We reviewed the page.
I don't even remember the student, if I could even call his name.
But he had about two pages of activities.
Excellent work, everything else.
And he got up here and he busted out after a year.
because he didn't have his priorities straight.
He was still participating in all the extracurricular activities and everything, and I think he stayed out a year or two.
I think he came back, and I think he graduated and did well, but it's one of those things when if you look at it on paper, there's no way in the world he could possibly not succeed.
But that's the other factor, which is so intangible, and that's their motivation and their application and things like this.
And that's where a lot of times you can take a student, after you've talked to them a while, I think you get a feel as to how they're going to perform and do certain things.
I mean, obviously, if they don't have some of the academic background, they're not going to be successful.
But if they've got the
what I would call the minimum academic background.
And if they're willing to work hard, if they come from a family which values work, discipline, and things like this, I'd take a chance on them because I think they would be successful.
They're not going to be a 4.0 student, but they're going to graduate.
And as we know from looking at statistics, a lot of those who graduated with minimal scores have done very well in the business world.
What about if they came from a non-native American born parent or parents?
Is that an advantage or a disadvantage in a marginal student's admission?
Their parents immigrated from somewhere.
Again, I don't know.
I wouldn't want to talk to the student.

I want to look at their academic background and so forth and sometimes even talking to their parents or knowing what their parents have done and everything because I think that sometimes the immigrants can instill in the students a worth ethic, which to me is still one of the most important things, that they've got a good worth.
work ethic, they can overcome some of the other things.
They have to maybe do different things.

They've got to have some good counseling when they get here and I always encouraged a student to not think they had to graduate in four years sometimes because sometimes they have to take the pace a little bit slower especially a lot of students are then and now are you know working
And a lot of them are taking much longer because of having to work or wanting to work, depending on which one it may be.
Like I heard the other day that somebody had seen an interview on national TV with Dat Nguyen and our, is it Dat or Nat?
Dat.
Dat Nguyen, our fine linebacker, and his parents.
And according to the person who watched the program, that his parents are barely,
competent in speaking English.
That wouldn't surprise me.
I think a lot of the first generation Vietnamese have not acquired a real skill with the language.
But here he's done well.
Income level would you give if a person was from a poor family as compared to a middle class or upper class family and marginal
Would you and your folks have been more likely to give that person a little extra chance on admission?
There may have been times.
I'm not saying we, if a kid had come from them.
an impoverished background, either financially or otherwise, but had worked hard and showed determination to succeed on the thing, yeah, we probably would give them a chance.
Again, I think that's one of those intangibles which you can't see on paper.
You can talk to people in this kind of thing.
But where it looks like they're overcoming some kind of a handicap, to me, which would indicate a good work ethic, we would probably have given them a chance on the thing.
Right.
So we become gradually more selective in the 70s and 80s in admissions here, is that correct?
That's correct.
Do you remember any specific change that caused more ripples than any other?
Was there a time when the admission requirement was modified and there were more howls?
I think there were howls.
We've had to limit the number, and it got worse early in the 90s, where we had to limit the number of freshmen that we can admit.
I mean, we set the limit.
Who set that limit, as far as you know?
When you say who set it, obviously the president set it.
Or the board, let me put it that way, it had to go to the board.
The board set the limit if they wanted the student body to be, and I think the figure was 40,000.
To keep it at 40,000, I think they decided that if you start off with 6,000 freshmen and allow X number of transfers to-
